	(text "* Power line outputs.\n* Preferrable to draw power from here\n  because these headers are able to\n  carry more current than the others.\n* Generally, 3A is the nominal limit,\n  with 5A for a short amount of time\n  (e.g. peak for a few seconds)."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 72.39 52.07 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.762 0.762)
				(color 72 72 72 1)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "3c66d98f-9d8b-4334-8572-e6bbfbaccb44")
	)
	(text "[util-button] Pin Headers and Connectors"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 66.04 20.32 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.778 1.778)
				(thickness 0.4064)
				(bold yes)
				(color 72 72 72 1)
			)
		)
		(uuid "4a14e717-5892-4d20-be17-a8c41324f665")
	)
	(text "* For connection with\n  a host (embedded\n  SoC/MCU, PC, etc.).\n* Only USER Bus exposed\n  (SCL_TX/SDA_RX), can\n  be either I2C or UART.\n  Internal Peripheral\n  bus only accessible\n  from the HAT Headers.\n* D+ and D- is bypassed\n  to the host, but no\n  MUX controls it. Host\n  must communicate with\n  the board to know when\n  it's safe to use.\n* ~{RST} and BOOT are\n  useful for programming\n  the host, especially\n  if they're ST MCUs.\n\n\n\n* Pins:\n  - SCL_TX: SCL (I2C) / TX (UART)\n  - SDA_RX: SDA (I2C) / RX (UART)\n  - ~{IRQB}: Smart interrupt bus\n  - VCC: Supply, 5V or 3.3V, 1A max\n  - ~{BTN}: User side-button\n  - ~{RST}: Physical RESET signal\n  - D+: USB's D+ data line\n  - D-: USB's D- data line\n  - BOOT: Physical BOOT signal\n  - 5V: 5V Supply line, 1A max"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 53.34 52.07 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.762 0.762)
				(color 72 72 72 1)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "90c13049-b2e7-40a5-849e-36b10c3f8cfe")
	)
	(text "* For SWD Programming\n  and debugging."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 38.1 124.46 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.762 0.762)
				(color 72 72 72 1)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "c538eb62-613f-4145-94a7-55f01d65f402")
	)
	(text "* For external extensibility (e.g. add OLED and buttons, etc.). Adds a \"HAT\" to the Board.\n* Board has two modes of operation: Standalone and Managed. In Managed Mode, only PHER bus\n  should be used by the HAT/shield. In Standalone mode, both PHER and USER buses can\n  be used safely. This is because in PHER, the board is Master; but in USER, board is Slave,\n  unless it's in Standalone mode. See the SoC (soc-control) sub-sheet for more details."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 38.1 110.49 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 0.762 0.762)
				(color 72 72 72 1)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "e5cfb2be-e585-4dfa-b6a9-fe52ed610fa7")
	)
